392
00:51:38,964 --> 00:51:41,934
Two different guns means two burglars.

393
00:51:42,301 --> 00:51:46,003
Two guys broke in? They both
went out the window? That's bullshit.

394
00:51:46,871 --> 00:51:47,838
By the way...

395
00:51:48,039 --> 00:51:52,510
...why he or they go out the window
in the first place, when he or they...

396
00:51:52,710 --> 00:51:55,779
...got in by breaking
a zillion-dollar security system?

397
00:51:56,546 --> 00:51:59,783
A Bill Burton from Secret Service
is in the parking lot.

398
00:51:59,983 --> 00:52:03,453
Thanks. What's Secret Service
doing in the parking lot?

399
00:52:11,961 --> 00:52:13,662
Bill Burton. Hi.

400
00:52:13,829 --> 00:52:16,297
Seth Frank.
To what do I owe the honor?

401
00:52:16,497 --> 00:52:21,302
I know you must be going crazy, but the
boss is interested about your progress.

402
00:52:21,502 --> 00:52:23,137
We could help each other out.

403
00:52:23,338 --> 00:52:24,806
What do you have in mind?

404
00:52:25,540 --> 00:52:27,841
You know how close he and Sullivan are.

405
00:52:28,008 --> 00:52:29,042
Right.

406
00:52:29,209 --> 00:52:30,310
Well.

407
00:52:31,178 --> 00:52:33,213
The minute anything breaks...

408
00:52:33,914 --> 00:52:36,049
...call me and I'll tell the president.

409
00:52:36,250 --> 00:52:40,186
He'd be the first to alert Mr. Sullivan.
It'd mean a lot to him.

410
00:52:40,753 --> 00:52:43,222
And any red tape you want cut, done.

411
00:52:44,590 --> 00:52:46,025
Here's my numbers.

412
00:52:47,360 --> 00:52:48,493
Any leads?

413
00:52:49,094 --> 00:52:51,429
We're still trying to figure it out.

414
00:52:51,596 --> 00:52:54,799
- I loved playing Sherlock Holmes.
- Secret Service guys do that?

415
00:52:55,033 --> 00:52:57,769
I was a state trooper before
the government got me.

416
00:52:57,969 --> 00:52:59,937
Wait. You're that Bill Burton?

417
00:53:00,104 --> 00:53:01,539
I was younger and dumber then.

418
00:53:01,705 --> 00:53:04,308
I was younger.
I think I'm dumber now.

419
00:53:04,408 --> 00:53:05,376
Keep in touch.

420
00:53:32,033 --> 00:53:35,136
My chef makes them especially for me.

421
00:53:35,303 --> 00:53:38,005
I promise you, they're sinful.

422
00:53:38,973 --> 00:53:40,975
You're a salesman, Mr. Sullivan.

423
00:53:42,509 --> 00:53:44,477
This is a new arena for me...

424
00:53:45,512 --> 00:53:47,480
...but from what I'm told, you...

425
00:53:47,681 --> 00:53:49,316
...have a flawless reputation...

426
00:53:49,849 --> 00:53:52,752
...which is why I need
to employ you, Mr. McCarty.

427
00:53:52,918 --> 00:53:53,953
Understood.

428
00:53:54,186 --> 00:53:57,089
I don't know who it is I'm after yet.

429
00:53:57,256 --> 00:53:58,724
Until I do...

430
00:53:58,891 --> 00:54:01,660
...you'll have to wait in Washington
for instructions.

431
00:54:04,028 --> 00:54:05,997
I'm afraid that's out of the question.

432
00:54:07,265 --> 00:54:09,033
My work is not very creative...

433
00:54:09,100 --> 00:54:11,903
...and I do it because I enjoy living
beyond my means.

434
00:54:12,070 --> 00:54:14,205
I can't afford to just sit around.

435
00:54:16,273 --> 00:54:19,343
My father died when
I was ten years old.

436
00:54:19,543 --> 00:54:20,911
He was a miner.

437
00:54:21,111 --> 00:54:22,880
He died of lung disease.

438
00:54:23,614 --> 00:54:26,082
I became rich at 25.

439
00:54:26,282 --> 00:54:29,619
The first thing I did was buy
that mine, close it down...

440
00:54:29,785 --> 00:54:33,756
...and give every miner
$50,000 to retire on.

441
00:54:36,958 --> 00:54:39,794
You will wait in Washington,
Mr. McCarty...

442
00:54:40,128 --> 00:54:41,596
...and I will put...

443
00:54:41,796 --> 00:54:44,266
...one million dollars expenses...

444
00:54:44,633 --> 00:54:46,867
...in a Swiss bank of your choosing...

445
00:54:47,067 --> 00:54:47,968
...and...

446
00:54:48,135 --> 00:54:49,603
...when the time comes...

447
00:54:49,970 --> 00:54:52,239
...two million dollars a bullet.

448
00:54:54,642 --> 00:54:56,544
You are a salesman, sir.

449
00:54:59,245 --> 00:55:01,447
Selling sin is easy.

450
00:55:08,154 --> 00:55:10,389
- Who is he?
- That's Luther Whitney...

451
00:55:10,589 --> 00:55:12,991
...one of the world's great thieves.

452
00:55:13,759 --> 00:55:16,495
I'm going nuts with this.
I was up all night.

453
00:55:18,130 --> 00:55:21,232
I remembered your notion about
how maybe it was two burglars.

454
00:55:21,432 --> 00:55:22,900
Around dawn I thought:

455
00:55:23,067 --> 00:55:26,070
What if it's not two burglars
but what if it's one guy...

456
00:55:26,204 --> 00:55:28,573
...trying to throw us off
by making it look like two?

457
00:55:28,940 --> 00:55:30,173
I called the FBI.

458
00:55:30,340 --> 00:55:32,475
They keep track of this stuff.

459
00:55:32,642 --> 00:55:36,112
There's maybe six guys who
could have done the Sullivan job.

460
00:55:36,213 --> 00:55:37,614
I've traced all six...

461
00:55:38,014 --> 00:55:40,183
...only Whitney lives in Washington.

462
00:55:40,784 --> 00:55:42,418
Why's it I never heard of him?

463
00:55:42,618 --> 00:55:44,954
'Cause he hasn't been arrested
in 30 years.

464
00:55:45,120 --> 00:55:47,923
What's this? His graduation picture
from Harvard?

465
00:55:48,123 --> 00:55:51,327
That's ancient history.
He was part of a gang.

466
00:55:51,527 --> 00:55:52,861
Three-time loser.

467
00:55:53,027 --> 00:55:54,829
Since he got out the last time...

468
00:55:55,296 --> 00:55:56,831
...no one's touched him.

469
00:55:58,032 --> 00:56:02,370
Anytime something big comes up
they question him, but it never sticks.

470
00:56:03,704 --> 00:56:05,439
We can make this stick.

471
00:56:06,540 --> 00:56:11,078
I bet this is our guy. He's local.
You can't ask for anything more.

472
00:56:11,879 --> 00:56:13,679
Well, we got a problem.

473
00:56:13,880 --> 00:56:14,947
What?

474
00:56:16,215 --> 00:56:18,417
He hasn't killed anyone in 45 years.

475
00:56:19,385 --> 00:56:20,520
Korea.

476
00:56:20,720 --> 00:56:22,288
So what, he's a veteran.

477
00:56:22,488 --> 00:56:25,524
He's not just a veteran.
He's a wounded veteran.

478
00:56:25,824 --> 00:56:27,726
I got his war record here.

479
00:56:28,059 --> 00:56:29,694
Battles, commendations...

480
00:56:29,895 --> 00:56:31,963
...decorations up the kazoo.

481
00:56:33,231 --> 00:56:35,199
He lives alone on his disability.

482
00:56:35,366 --> 00:56:37,835
That's what he says anyway. But...

483
00:56:38,402 --> 00:56:41,972
I don't see this guy as a killer.
He's just a great thief.

484
00:56:42,172 --> 00:56:44,575
Besides, I don't do war heroes.

485
00:57:31,283 --> 00:57:32,985
Well, you must be smart.

486
00:57:34,386 --> 00:57:35,588
Pardon me?

487
00:57:36,722 --> 00:57:39,591
Usually it takes you guys
a week to get to me.

488
00:57:43,895 --> 00:57:45,230
I recognize your picture...

489
00:57:45,396 --> 00:57:46,631
...from the newspaper.

490
00:57:49,734 --> 00:57:51,101
Nice to meet you.

491
00:57:52,069 --> 00:57:56,707
Would you like a signed confession now,
or would you like to have coffee first?

492
00:57:56,907 --> 00:58:00,944
Before I send you away for life,
I should check out your alibi.

493
00:58:01,878 --> 00:58:03,379
I was watching football...

494
00:58:03,579 --> 00:58:05,715
...with a friend, Red Bransford.

495
00:58:05,915 --> 00:58:07,950
He owns a saloon here in town.

496
00:58:08,918 --> 00:58:12,888
You can ask me about the game
if you like. I could be lying.

497
00:58:14,089 --> 00:58:15,724
You've been following the case?

498
00:58:15,924 --> 00:58:17,158
I have.

499
00:58:17,325 --> 00:58:19,294
I love true crime.

500
00:58:19,761 --> 00:58:24,398
FBI says only a few guys could handle
the Sullivan job. I got a list.

501
00:58:24,598 --> 00:58:25,900
You're on it.

502
00:58:26,433 --> 00:58:28,068
How I wish it were true.

503
00:58:30,337 --> 00:58:32,106
This person, they...

504
00:58:32,406 --> 00:58:37,243
...they go in the front door, then out
a window and down a rope at night?

505
00:58:37,777 --> 00:58:42,682
If I could do something like that I'd
be the star of my A.A.R.P. Meetings.

506
00:58:43,850 --> 00:58:45,317
What, the American...?

507
00:58:45,484 --> 00:58:48,187
Association of Retired Persons.

508
00:58:51,023 --> 00:58:53,325
Luther, why was this so difficult?

509
00:58:54,026 --> 00:58:56,661
You want me to help you
solve your case?

510
00:58:56,861 --> 00:58:58,596
Just looking for insight.

511
00:58:58,763 --> 00:58:59,997
How would you...

512
00:59:00,631 --> 00:59:03,334
Scratch that.
How would one go about it?

513
00:59:03,534 --> 00:59:06,002
What kind of person should I look for?

514
00:59:07,871 --> 00:59:11,107
Except for the rope trick,
an older person. Like me.

515
00:59:11,308 --> 00:59:12,642
Because?

516
00:59:13,543 --> 00:59:15,345
Well, you need patience.

517
00:59:15,512 --> 00:59:18,881
The secret is research.
At least I've read that.

518
00:59:19,048 --> 00:59:20,683
What kind of research?

519
00:59:22,551 --> 00:59:26,121
From what I saw on the tube,
this is a rather large home.

520
00:59:26,322 --> 00:59:28,790
There must be an architectural office.

521
00:59:29,057 --> 00:59:32,527
You'd have to go to the library,
go through public records...

522
00:59:32,727 --> 00:59:36,631
...find out where that office is
and then you break in.

523
00:59:36,831 --> 00:59:39,666
You xerox the plans and
get them back by morning.

524
00:59:39,833 --> 00:59:41,502
Why not just steal them?

525
00:59:42,169 --> 00:59:44,705
Anyone can break in, but breaking in...

526
00:59:44,905 --> 00:59:48,141
...without people knowing it,
that's the trick.

527
00:59:48,308 --> 00:59:50,710
Then there's the general contractor...

528
00:59:50,910 --> 00:59:53,346
...and there's the security company.

529
00:59:53,846 --> 00:59:58,251
Do you realize the skill in breaking
the security of a security company?

530
00:59:59,218 --> 01:00:01,520
I don't know how those guys do it.

531
01:00:03,355 --> 01:00:05,490
Why go to all that trouble?

532
01:00:06,591 --> 01:00:10,428
It's a large vault. There must be
a secret way into it.

533
01:00:10,595 --> 01:00:12,897
There was, that's what I don't get.

534
01:00:13,531 --> 01:00:14,698
How do you mean?

535
01:00:14,865 --> 01:00:18,269
This guy had obviously done
the research you're talking about.

536
01:00:18,435 --> 01:00:21,172
So why take a crowbar
to open this vault...

537
01:00:21,372 --> 01:00:23,540
...when there's a clicker right there?

538
01:00:23,740 --> 01:00:24,674
Clicker?

539
01:00:25,441 --> 01:00:28,077
Gizmo. Like a VCR remote.

540
01:00:30,613 --> 01:00:32,581
Sounds amazing to me.

541
01:00:34,216 --> 01:00:36,852
Must have been a lot of valuables
in that vault.

542
01:00:40,622 --> 01:00:43,257
Close to five million, total value.

543
01:00:45,560 --> 01:00:46,894
Is that funny?

544
01:00:47,261 --> 01:00:49,430
Are you trying to surprise me?

545
01:00:49,630 --> 01:00:51,199
I was trying to surprise you.

546
01:00:51,399 --> 01:00:53,034
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

547
01:00:55,101 --> 01:00:56,436
There you go again.

548
01:01:00,907 --> 01:01:03,443
Would the burglar use a disguise?

549
01:01:03,743 --> 01:01:04,777
He might.

550
01:01:05,411 --> 01:01:08,447
Get with the program,
if you want to catch this guy.

551
01:01:08,647 --> 01:01:12,618
It is a guy, we think?
Some sort of a loner? Weirdo, yeah?

552
01:01:12,818 --> 01:01:14,053
Maybe like you.

553
01:01:15,620 --> 01:01:18,790
I'd be the perfect prototype, actually.

554
01:01:18,990 --> 01:01:22,760
But you see a person long enough,
you start putting things together.

555
01:01:22,927 --> 01:01:25,964
That's why these top guys
have disguises.

556
01:01:26,230 --> 01:01:29,399
Some of them, I understand,
become make-up experts.

557
01:01:29,600 --> 01:01:31,969
Hire wigmakers and things like that.

558
01:01:32,436 --> 01:01:34,571
Why don't you go on
about the wigmakers?

559
01:01:34,771 --> 01:01:35,806
Well, I would...

560
01:01:36,673 --> 01:01:39,108
I must go have my pacemaker checked.

561
01:01:39,275 --> 01:01:41,677
It's been so exciting talking to you.

562
01:01:42,345 --> 01:01:46,082
A: You don't have a pacemaker.
And B: I'll be back tomorrow.

563
01:01:47,283 --> 01:01:49,751
Tomorrow is promised to no one.

564
01:01:53,088 --> 01:01:54,322
Good-bye.

565
01:01:59,293 --> 01:02:01,428
Pacemaker, my ass.

566
01:03:02,551 --> 01:03:04,052
Oh, Katie.

567
01:03:05,086 --> 01:03:08,022
You must start eating
better than this, darling.

568
01:03:11,759 --> 01:03:14,394
I'm having this
press conference here...

569
01:03:15,696 --> 01:03:18,599
...because it is at this courthouse...

570
01:03:19,500 --> 01:03:23,303
...that Christine Sullivan's killer
will be tried for his crime.

